      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200 mb-2">1. Resistance to Cracking & Ground Movement</h3>
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-pretty">
            Poured concrete acts as a single, rigid sheet. When the soil below freezes, swells, or settles, the tensile stress forces concrete to crack. Control joints help guide these cracks, but cannot prevent them. 
          </p>
          <p class="mt-2 leading-relaxed text-pretty">
            Pavers are individual interlocking pieces resting on compacted sand and gravel. This modular design allows the surface to flex and move with the earth, completely eliminating surface cracking.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 dark:text-neutral-200 mb-2">2. Maintenance & Long-Term Costs</h3>
          <p class="leading-relaxed text-pretty">
            Concrete requires sealing every 2 to 3 years to prevent moisture absorption and staining. If concrete cracks or stains heavily, repairs require patching (which leaves visible scars) or jackhammering the entire slab.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-2 leading-relaxed text-pretty">
            Pavers require regular weed control in the joints and occasional polymer sand replenishment. However, if a single paver is damaged or stained by oil, you can pull it out individually and replace it in minutes.
          </p>
